children.name: Text
children.value: The children don't care for chocolate anymore now that they can eat scrummy ice cream every day.

children.name: Text
children.value: Metals are sucked into the stratosphere, clinging to it, until finally it comes crashing back down to earth.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Electric Potato Harvester 2205

children.name: Text
children.value: Harvests gold and potatoes simultaneously. In the future we'll all be stupid rich, sitting on mountains of potatoes!

children.name: Text
children.value: Stripped to the bare essentials, this new type of Airship gondola will grant your zeppelin that extra bit of zip.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Dedicated Airship hoist

children.name: Text
children.value: Offers accelerated cargo loading and improved weight distribution for your skybound pride and joy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Their eyes are listless, their faces gaunt and grey — Qumaq was right — the survivors barely look human anymore.

children.name: Text
children.value: The writings of Sir John Faithful upon his expedition's departure inland from the initial camp at King William Island.

children.name: Text
children.value: A team of hardened Explorers raring to shift the icy impediment between them and Sir John's expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: A fragment of Sir John Faithful's Logbook, from a fraught leg of the expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: Keen to construct a research station in the far North, and understand recent strange phenomena.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not the popsicle flavour I'd choose...

children.name: Text
children.value: Contains clues as to the whereabouts of a certain research station.

children.name: Text
children.value: A bit chilly after being thrown overboard, but in good spirits.

children.name: Text
children.value: Inexperienced now, yes, but in time they'll learn.

children.name: Text
children.value: A delightful hair separator of great sentimental value.

children.name: Text
children.value: A tart berry with well-documented healing properties that the Inuit eat to relieve colds and sore throats.

children.name: Text
children.value: Help Lady Faithful rescue her husband in The Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: The blizzard has utterly destroyed the resolve of your crew. The Captain agrees the only option is to turn back, and return to the Arctic when the expedition is better prepared to face its challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: The polar bear attack has utterly destroyed the resolve of your crew. The Captain agrees the only option is to turn back, and return to the Arctic when the expedition is better prepared to face its challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Iceberg has utterly destroyed the resolve of your crew. The Captain agrees the only option is to turn back, and return to the Arctic when the expedition is better prepared to face its challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: The incident on the ice has utterly destroyed the resolve of your crew. The Captain agrees the only option is to turn back, and return to the Arctic when the expedition is better prepared to face its challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: The narrow channels have utterly destroyed the resolve of your crew. The Captain agrees the only option is to turn back, and return to the Arctic when the expedition is better prepared to face its challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: You landed at Baffling Island, where you found clues as to where the lost expedition was headed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Circumventing Labrador Island from the West, you navigated some narrow channels.

children.name: Text
children.value: Circumventing Labrador Island from the East, your ship was stranded on an iceberg.

children.name: Text
children.value: You had to cross a perilous ice sheet.

children.name: Text
children.value: You reached the Huddlesome Bay Trading Post, which has been abandoned for years.

children.name: Text
children.value: Walking in the open, you risked an encounter with polar bears.

children.name: Text
children.value: You arrived at the Inuit settlement.

children.name: Text
children.value: [Participants Current Profile CompanyName] settles first island in The Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: The people are giddy with excitement in [Newspaper FindArticle([RefGuid]) Context TownName] now that the new Airship Hangar is finished, and wonder when peculiar flying contraptions are likely to start rumbling through its doors.

children.name: Text
children.value: Townsfolk are raising their heads in disbelief to stare at the newly-constructed airship whose shadow now envelops them. Dwarfing even some of the largest buildings, the airship is a windborne warehouse, a depot flotante, a mechanical, mercurial, trans-continental, aeolian zephyr!

children.name: Text
children.value: Lady Jane Faithful, is gathering the world's best to conduct full and final search of her own; Two years since Sir John Faithful's expedition to the Northwest Passage was declared lost in the Arctic, the Captain's strong-willed wife, says she will not rest "until they are fed, bathed in hot salts and tucked up in their beds."

children.name: Text
children.value: Sir John and Lady Jane reunited! Lady Faithful praises crucial work of [Participants Current Profile CompanyName]. Three heroic survivors returned to their loved ones at long last! Sir John Faithful decorated for his courageous leadership! Claims they partook in anthropophagy vehemently denied — they definitely did not eat each other!

children.name: Text
children.value: THE LOST EXPEDITION OF SIR JOHN FAITHFUL

children.name: Text
children.value: The expedition to find the Northwest Passage of Sir John Faithful went missing!

children.name: Text
children.value: THE LOST EXPEDITION OF SIR JOHN FAITHFUL

children.name: Text
children.value: The expedition to find the Northwest Passage of Sir John Faithful went missing!

children.name: Text
children.value: Zeppelin technician in the Arctic claims the human race began there, "If I told you the many rock and ice formations we have found look eerily human, you'd probably laugh," he tells us, "but we know the human body is eighty-percent water, so you do the maths."

children.name: Text
children.value: Arctic braggart keen to show off his mountaineering prowess foiled by the obvious fact that the photograph was taken from the air. Nevertheless his research on the mountain chain and glacier looks promising according to sources at the Goldfurt Geographical Institute...(article continues in this week's natural science supplement)

children.value: A residence lacking a nearby ranger station is suffering from Arctic Flu!

children.value: ArcticIllness Ongoing Consumed a Building NotificationText

children.value: Ongoing Arctic Flu has left one of your buildings in ruins!

children.value: Arctic Flu in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] is out of control!

children.name: Text
children.value: Arctic Flu in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] has cleared up.

children.value: Arctic Flu caused buildings to be abandoned in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName].

children.value: An ongoing fire has consumed one of your buildings!

children.value: Fire in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] is out of control!

children.name: Text
children.value: Fire in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] extinguished.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fire in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] extinguished, but has caused damage.

children.name: Text
children.value: You're running out of coal in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName]!

children.value: A heater in [NotificationContext Value(Area) Area CityName] is out of [NotificationContext Value(Object) Object Factory Inputs AT(0) Product Text] and isn't working anymore.

children.name: Text
children.value: because of a lack of heat!

children.name: Text
children.value: Find Sir John Faithful's lost expedition to the Northwest Passage (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Complete 10 Inuit or arctic residents' quests (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Complete all the cultural sets from the Arctic (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Don’t build a Charcoal Kiln in the Arctic until you pass 1000 Technicians (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Having passed 500 technicians, turn off Heaters heating residences for 60 minutes (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Build one Hangar on each of the 4 Arctic Plateaus (The Passage).

children.name: Text
children.value: Scrap from bygone expeditions that ventured to the ice desert.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can be found in the ice desert.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can be found in the ice desert.

children.name: Text
children.value: Feel down? Tickle yourself with these.

children.name: Text
children.value: A Light in the darkness. Smells.

children.name: Text
children.value: Yell "Nanuk" and your huskies might go faster.

children.name: Text
children.value: This isn't the kind of winter wonderland your Visitors expect.

children.name: Text
children.value: No Working Conditions in the Arctic

children.name: Text
children.value: Your Arctic heroes are already giving it everything they have.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you dare to face the challenges of the Arctic? Venture to the edge of the world; conquer the most hostile of environments with a brand new heating system, build monumental hangars to claim the sky with your very own airships, and assist Lady Jane Faithful in her quest to find her husband, Sir John, and his lost expedition to the Northwest Passage...

children.name: Text
children.value: Conquer the Arctic's extreme conditions, with new residents and production chains.

children.name: Text
children.value: Look for the Lost Expedition alongside new and familiar characters, like Lady Faithful, Old Nate, and the Inuit shaman Qumaq.

children.name: Text
children.value: Light up your megapolis with a much more efficient gas-fired power plant that doesn't require a railway connection!

children.name: Text
children.value: Construct your own airships and be the first to raise above your competitors!

children.name: Text
children.value: Bring the spirit of the holidays to Anno 1800 with this new cosmetic DLC pack, which includes 23 new ornaments.

children.name: Text
children.value: You will find the Holiday ornaments under this category in the construction menu:

children.name: Text
children.value: Newspaper effects do not affect residents of The Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: We can't deliver newspapers all the way to the Arctic!

children.name: Text
children.value: Cannot destroy! Airship is carrying a Quest Item.

children.name: Text
children.value: You must own an airship to transmute with Old Nate in The Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: The sum of all heat factors.

children.name: Text
children.value: Freezing residents may get Arctic Flu and spread it.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Airship Hangar is built in phases. Once complete, it can produce Trade Airships if you have a supply of gas.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hardly more than a dream traced in the snow, for now. But the foundations of the Hangar are ready to be ploughed and consolidated in reality — to take you one step closer to the clouds.

children.name: Text
children.value: The ice-cold steel structure of the Hangar raises from the ground like the stranded carcass of a colossal whale. Yet one musn't be fooled by the striking morbidness of the image: this whale will give birth to airships.

children.name: Text
children.value: The vast dome is nearly finished. Once the canvas roofing is streched over the skeleton and the technical equipment installed, the assembly of airships will commence.

children.name: Text
children.value: A trading vessel that flies! Especially suitable for long-distance trades. Has fewer cargo slots, but can travel much faster. No technology exists to shoot them down...yet.

children.name: Text
children.value: Extracts raw gas from gas deposits.

children.name: Text
children.value: Provides heat in a limited area if supplied with Coal.

children.name: Text
children.value: Provides heat to connected residences and factories.

children.name: Text
children.value: Connected residences and factories are no longer being supplied with heat.

children.name: Text
children.value: Only useful if equipped with items. Attach items here to provide bonuses to residences and production.

children.name: Text
children.value: Consumes Gas to provide Electricity to nearby buildings.

children.name: Text
children.value: There's always a chance residents may catch Arctic Flu. Residents in better heated areas are less likely to fall ill, and Ranger Stations can also reduce the chance of Arctic Flu appearing.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fights fire and Arctic Flu in its influence radius.

children.name: Text
children.value: Progress in the story of The Passage

children.name: Text
children.value: An airship is needed to access Old Nate's workshop.

children.name: Text
children.value: The most ambitious rescue I've had the honour to be part of.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hoped and feared I might one day have the privilege of such an undertaking.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can we do worse than the Arctic council? They're afraid of the ice in their whisky!

children.name: Text
children.value: I will not rest while fellow seamen succumb to the cold, we are with you!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Northwest passage is uncharted, Admiral. More than preparation, we need luck.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't want to join the many that tried and failed to find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Seaman's intuition tells me they came this way, but I've been wrong before.

children.name: Text
children.value: I fear we may be as lost as the original expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let's hope we warm mother nature's frozen heart soon.

children.name: Text
children.value: The chill already gnaws at the bones of our crew.

children.name: Text
children.value: If I know Sir John Faithful right, I'd say he came this way.

children.name: Text
children.value: If these men seem impervious to cold, it's Lady Faithful's fire we have to thank.

children.name: Text
children.value: I've met few so hardy as Lady Faithful, we can't let her down now.

children.name: Text
children.value: And I thought the Arctic Council's efforts were pathetic.

children.name: Text
children.value: We might have turned back long ago, had the mysteries of the ice not drawn us in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Even I have rarely seen such extremes, and worse may be yet to come.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's a cairn o'rocks stacked by human hand! We have stumbled upon Sir John Faithful's last encampment!

children.name: Text
children.value: We've found no trace of Sir John and his crew, let us hope there is time to try again.

children.name: Text
children.value: We must be better prepared if we are to follow in the fateful footsteps of Sir John.

children.name: Text
children.value: I knew another captain who ventured this far north, but I know him no more.

children.name: Text
children.value: We all know this could be our last expedition, so may it be a fine one!

children.name: Text
children.value: If we die in the attempt, it won't be for a lack of commitment.

children.name: Text
children.value: It'll be the stuff of folklore if we succeed and bring back Sir John.

children.name: Text
children.value: Bears, vicious whales and restless spirits await us, if the tales are to be believed.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's a lot to ask, but to a seaman there's no challenge to rival the Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: A wise seaman would trust the Inuits. They know their land better than we ever will.

children.name: Text
children.value: I myself have little experience of the Arctic, but stand beside you.

children.name: Text
children.value: We shouldn't expect to find them right away...this is a vast wilderness.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's been two years, the Admiralty say they have tried everything, but then, they haven't lost a husband.

children.name: Text
children.value: —nor did it occur to them to search King William Sound— There! A camp!

children.name: Text
children.value: But we imagined as much, didn't we?—and my John picked a fine spot—perhaps they left some sign as to where they went…

children.name: Text
children.value: My name is Lady Jane Faithful, and it is my husband, Sir John, whose expedition is lost in the Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: In two years, the admiralty haven't done much about his rescue, but fortunately, I have.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have gathered men and resources to conquer the ice, and to you I offer a handsome reward for bringing him home.

children.name: Text
children.value: My John's camp shall serve for us. From here we can search to any length and breadth.

children.name: Text
children.value: Just as they left it. We'll rake over the remains, and then make a refuge for ourselves.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hold hard! A craig, heaped by highland hand, is well worth our time.

children.name: Text
children.value: I did say there would be rewards. That's for finding my John's camp.

children.name: Text
children.value: John's log, open it!— He knew we would come for him.

children.name: Text
children.value: If HMS Hades and Styx came this way, the Inuit must have seen them; maybe they can help us.

children.name: Text
children.value: That's the hangar? How marvellous! Sir John will be the first to congratulate you when we find him.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Hades and Styx came this way, if it take our last breath we must find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Here's something more. It'll take our best efforts to clear that frozen channel.

children.name: Text
children.value: We pick up our crumbs and prepare an especial ice-breaching brigade.

children.name: Text
children.value: Either we break through that ice, or else we go home now.

children.name: Text
children.value: What does it take for a captain to abandon his ship? To cross the ice by foot?

children.name: Text
children.value: How far did they really expect to take those boats?

children.name: Text
children.value: No ship, even an icebreaker, can carry us from here, nor will we cover enough ground on foot...

children.name: Text
children.value: Expensive yes, but with airships you'll be the one to find my John and his boys, I'm certain of it.

children.name: Text
children.value: The cost and scale of that structure is staggering. But have faith— my John is a risk-taker also.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now the search can really begin. From high above, this white expanse may seem more finite.

children.name: Text
children.value: Recommence the search where we left it; at the place the Hades and the Styx were abandoned.

children.name: Text
children.value: Follow their aura, as others have done, and we can still find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of the Inuit is offering to lead you north, I..I'd only be a hindrance, I'll wait for you on the other side.

children.name: Text
children.value: Say whatever you like John, I did everything I could to find you, and have absolutely no intention of giving up now.

children.name: Text
children.value: I am sorry about Sir John. He's had a hard time, they all have.

children.name: Text
children.value: I am ever so grateful to you, and do not think I have forgotten your reward, but for now I must get my dear husband home.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has his quirks, but he is the best, and that is precisely what we need.

children.name: Text
children.value: Young and brave are our volunteer Explorers, they will soon have the measure of the place.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technicians are a difficult lot, but their confidence does appear justified.

children.name: Text
children.value: ...something extra to keep everyone's spirits up...

children.name: Text
children.value: To ignore the wisdom of the Inuit is an arrogance we cannot afford.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is bitterly, bitterly cold. Make sure everyone keeps wrapped up.

children.name: Text
children.value: This encampment must embody hope, our one comfort in the wilderness.

children.name: Text
children.value: Last night I had a disquieting dream— we cannot allow time to run out.

children.name: Text
children.value: No small disappointment can cause me to give up hope.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'll not rest 'til my John is fed, bathed in hot salts and tucked up in bed.

children.name: Text
children.value: The ice is as old as time, and more stubborn than I ever believed.

children.name: Text
children.value: My husband is a stubborn man, I hope he was not too proud to heed the Inuit.

children.name: Text
children.value: I promised I would reward you, and now I have. And thank you, thank you for bringing back my dear John.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have no idea expensive that will be, but here. I hope that's a start.

children.name: Text
children.value: Our efforts should not diminish until the missing are accounted for.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have proven all is still possible.

children.name: Text
children.value: You endure where others have not.

children.name: Text
children.value: Just when I was beginning to lose faith.

children.name: Text
children.value: If we all pull together, who knows what we can achieve.

children.name: Text
children.value: We cannot allow this to stop us believing.

children.name: Text
children.value: We have let a chance pass us by.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now I feel the wind begin to bite.

children.name: Text
children.value: Too late, too late, they’re all dead. My impudence before the gods; we were doomed from the beginning. My stubbornness— my vile, reckless ambition. I should have died out there with them. I should have died!

children.name: Text
children.value: John no more, I am a phantom, my love; an exile condemned to this twilight plane for eternity.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ha. I never could argue with you.

children.name: Text
children.value: So help me god, get the fires started or the lot of us will freeze!

children.name: Text
children.value: You might want to start looking for coal.

children.name: Text
children.value: Wotcha! I'll be joining you. Lady Faithful's engaged me for some practical advice— gonna be dead cold up there.

children.name: Text
children.value: S'cold enough to freeze the balls off a brass monkey, gorr, get the coal fires burning posthaste.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ahh, that's nice on the hands, keep it stoked or we'll catch our deaths out here.

children.name: Text
children.value: First get all ye faithful some shelter, and a canteen where they can warm each other up.

children.name: Text
children.value: The heat of them heaters don't travel far, and most of your buildings'll need heating and all.

children.name: Text
children.value: You need a bloomin' airship, you do. Eh, what do you mean borrow mine?—get out of it!

children.name: Text
children.value: Why not build yer own airships? You'll want to employ a lot of fusspot pseuds though, so watch out.

children.name: Text
children.value: Build a hangar first; good thought. Better hope the ice don't melt, or that'll be the first thing to go.

children.name: Text
children.value: What's that you say? No gas? Gorrr….very well, I s'pose I'll have to lend you some.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pffft Pffft Pffft, can't stop gassing out here, got to keep chattering to stay afloat.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your first ruddy airship, I bet you feel lighter-than-air!

children.name: Text
children.value: If you can't squeeze it out of old Archie, I've seen gas come out the ground to the north.

children.name: Text
children.value: There! Glad I don't have to be yer pump attendant no more, the cheek of it, I ask yer…

children.name: Text
children.value: Didn't eat each other?! Got to be pulling my leg… oh, too soon?

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh! This is some scrap from William Perry's failed expedition— still good for a lot of things.

children.name: Text
children.value: Bet there's more scrap out there from all the other failed expeditions, bring it 'ere, and I'll transmute it.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've a responsibility to Sir John to gather up his valuables as we go. Hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Lady Faithful hopes to revive her marriage, but Sir John's got cold feet, hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gorr those Explorers are keen, actually no, they're stark raving mad.

children.name: Text
children.value: Jumped-up little gits them Technicians, dunno why I put up with 'em.

children.name: Text
children.value: I like that the Inuit use every part of the animal.

children.name: Text
children.value: One good thing about the Arctic, equipment don't decompose like cadavers do.

children.name: Text
children.value: A lot of people tried before Sir John Faithful, left a lot of scrap up in the ice channels.

children.name: Text
children.value: Got me own Huddlesome Bay Company.

children.name: Text
children.value: Got to be resourceful up here, eh.

children.name: Text
children.value: Keep an eye out for scrap from lost expeditions.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you take yer eye off the heaters, temperatures'll plummet.

children.name: Text
children.value: So cold, you can hear their bones starting to creak.

children.name: Text
children.value: Been a lot easier if Sir John'd had airships in the first place.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's expensive enough running one airship.

children.name: Text
children.value: What can I say, hangars take up a lot of space.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't like 'em neither, but you need Technicians to have airships.

children.name: Text
children.value: It shows we have conquered our fear.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have done well, and you smell nice.

children.name: Text
children.value: When the ice breaks, I want you there with me.

children.name: Text
children.value: The wolf has kept you strong, caribou.

children.name: Text
children.value: There is much to be afraid of now.

children.name: Text
children.value: I must consult the spirit now.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is an ill wind that blows nobody any good.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have damaged the balance of things.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have let many people down.

children.name: Text
children.value: A shaman must help those in need. We will share what we know.

children.name: Text
children.value: We were afraid you would come for them. Now you are here we must help you.

children.name: Text
children.value: To know where you are going, you have to know where you come from.

children.name: Text
children.value: A fur hood would help shake the snow from your face.

children.name: Text
children.value: We do not camp anywhere long, the season changes fast.

children.name: Text
children.value: The igluit are made with anything we can find.

children.name: Text
children.value: During the long dark winter, we will play games and tell stories.

children.name: Text
children.value: Seal is important to us, we are careful to waste no part of it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Take only the whale and bear that you need.

children.name: Text
children.value: May you have warmth in your iglu.

children.name: Text
children.value: May you have oil in your lamp.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go with peace in your heart.

children.name: Text
children.value: Skins can be sewn into clothing with bone needles.

children.name: Text
children.value: You need a lot of good fat to reach the heart of ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate reminds me of Keelut, who leaves no tracks when feasting on the dead.

children.name: Text
children.value: Act not for yourself, but for the community.

children.name: Text
children.value: It makes no sense for me to be using a schooner, but there we go.

children.name: Text
children.value: I fear they went looking for the heart of ice. We have not seen them for a long time.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can set you on a path, the rest is down to you.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you tread carefully, then perhaps a way can be found.

children.name: Text
children.value: That is the way. Their breath still hangs in the air.

children.name: Text
children.value: Without belief, answers do not yet exist.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't know if your icebreaker will vanquish the ice, but we will not stand in your way.

children.name: Text
children.value: None of us have much time.

children.name: Text
children.value: You need to make the best of all you have.

children.name: Text
children.value: Such strength can redeem your people.

children.name: Text
children.value: This place is all-powerful, ever-changing, you have to adapt.

children.name: Text
children.value: We have sighted vessels stranded in the channels. They too will be lost without help.

children.name: Text
children.value: Better to let others learn from their own mistakes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your countrymen will soon become snowbound, and easy prey for Akhlut.

children.name: Text
children.value: Those men underestimated this place, but you can show them their failings.

children.name: Text
children.value: They will be glad to come back to light and hospitality, and think on their mistakes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Seals are everywhere; know how to look for them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nanurjuk says they didn't seem right. They said little as if their tongues were cut.

children.name: Text
children.value: They refused the seals we offered them.

children.name: Text
children.value: They would not trade, or drink soup with us.

children.name: Text
children.value: We built them a shelter, but they were already gone, deep into the ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Never have I seen beings so pale.

children.name: Text
children.value: They went beyond the old ice, to a place of danger.

children.name: Text
children.value: We are afraid Anguta has taken them to the underworld.

children.name: Text
children.value: There are many ways to survive here, we have learned since childhood.

children.name: Text
children.value: We were scared they were possessed by demons.

children.name: Text
children.value: They brought sickness with them, and devilry.

children.name: Text
children.value: We knew you would come for them, we have been waiting for you.

children.name: Text
children.value: If these are indeed humans you pursue, I will do all I can to help you.

children.name: Text
children.value: There are many things I could tell you, but I don't think they will help.

children.name: Text
children.value: There are many sea mammals here, Sedna is their keeper.

children.name: Text
children.value: We do not meddle in the business of others.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't expect to learn everything in a day.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Council have praised our knowledge, but never respected it.

children.name: Text
children.value: The vessels you seek are near yet far. Best prepare for terror.

children.name: Text
children.value: If their vessels drifted to a dark place, maybe they are there still.

children.name: Text
children.value: They could not have escaped the channels, you will find them there.

children.name: Text
children.value: We too want answers, you are brave to keep digging.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is a place of death. You can die here without knowing.

children.name: Text
children.value: I will not go with you. I hope it is men you find, at the end of your journey.

children.name: Text
children.value: When wise men die, the heavens lament.

children.name: Text
children.value: You are on the last floe now, but the most fragile.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have brought men back from the edge, you have earned our respect.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you cannot save them, their souls will be trapped in the upper world to starve for eternity.

children.name: Text
children.value: The lights in the sky cleave heads from the unworthy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Where the ice between the dead and the living is thinnest, you float across.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have no power to protect you, when you go to that place.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have stirred the wrath of the moon!

children.name: Text
children.value: Do not hunt alone, in darkness, or the wolf will take you.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is a celestial place, be wary of taboo.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fear this place, or it will take you smiling.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nanook decides if you may hunt, or if you violate this place.

children.name: Text
children.value: Inuksuk said he saw the white people carrying human meat.

children.name: Text
children.value: I remember they were so dirty,  they had lost all humanity.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you hear a whistling, it is their ghosts, trapped in the upper world.

children.name: Text
children.value: You saw Amarok. He preys upon those that stray too far from the path.

children.name: Text
children.value: I cannot say. The spirits become restless when strangers enter their realm. If we stay too long, they will never let us leave.

children.name: Text
children.value: Glorious it is when wandering time comes.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you walk on thin ice, you may as well dance.

children.name: Text
children.value: Be the lead dog, and show where to go.

children.name: Text
children.value: We should do what we can to survive.

children.name: Text
children.value: We should take gifts when they are offered.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is easy to underestimate this place.

children.name: Text
children.value: We waste no chance we have here.

children.name: Text
children.value: The day is young, there is more to do.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you share with the hunting party?

children.name: Text
children.value: There is nothing more to be said.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is a time of silence.

children.name: Text
children.value: We need more blubber for the kudliks.

children.name: Text
children.value: A boy who provides is a man.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hear the ice cracking? Time to hunt seal.

children.name: Text
children.value: Want to help us catch goose?

children.name: Text
children.value: Alpaca wool is warm you say?

children.name: Text
children.value: Warm, but not as warm as a parka of seal or caribou skin.

children.name: Text
children.value: No wind, no need for sails.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pigs are so friendly, but will not survive the cold.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your fish oil tastes like it's bad for you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you mean snow goggles, or something else?

children.name: Text
children.value: Very clever things if you have bad eyesight— I don't know anyone with bad eyesight.

children.name: Text
children.value: I drank it and couldn't sleep! If you work all day, you need to sleep.

children.name: Text
children.value: Some children snuck off to see your city, please can you send them home?

children.name: Text
children.value: Good, I don't want them to pick up habits. Our community will make them feel loved again.

children.name: Text
children.value: What kind of weather is it out there? What shape are the clouds?

children.name: Text
children.value: No clouds? Then Silla has been kind, and we have good hunting weather.

children.name: Text
children.value: See the natural formation near camp, do you know of any others?

children.name: Text
children.value: You found a lucky spot. When we next move camp we will move there.

children.name: Text
children.value: She is one of Sedna's great sharks, I wonder what happened to her.

children.name: Text
children.value: The creature is gone. Our thanks to you for driving it away.

children.name: Text
children.value: Look! Something damaged your boat! Maybe the wolf-whale Akhlut, come away!

children.name: Text
children.value: Can your machine find my amulet? I lost it to the sea in a storm.

children.name: Text
children.value: A great wave took many hunters.

children.name: Text
children.value: Built a camp and killed a bear to survive? We underestimated them, they have grown up fast.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Giant drank so much water she burst open, and fog was born.

children.name: Text
children.value: The fire is clearing the fog.

children.name: Text
children.value: The lamp has run low, the fog will not clear.

children.name: Text
children.value: The fog is lifted. Thank you.

children.name: Text
children.value: More clues, you are getting close.

children.name: Text
children.value: This track leads in a new direction.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is his first crime, we will talk to him and make him feel loved.

children.name: Text
children.value: He who stole ran into the mountains. I am worried for him.

children.name: Text
children.value: Everyone has bad sore throats. The elder went over the mountain for cranberries, but he hasn't returned.

children.name: Text
children.value: Footprints! Why did the elder abandon his sled?

children.name: Text
children.value: He came to this cave to die. When you have covered him with stones, gather the cranberries.

children.name: Text
children.value: The cranberries will make us better. Will you help us light a fire for the elder?

children.name: Text
children.value: Our community won't forget the elder's sacrifice, or yours.

children.name: Text
children.value: I feared you would come. I will show you where those men went.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ice has closed the way forward, to the place they took their boats.

children.name: Text
children.value: The storm makes it hard to see.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do not become them— I will help you find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: They abandoned the boats… will you seek them with this bird of yours?

children.name: Text
children.value: I dislike it in the clouds. There— clear tracks leading away from the boats.

children.name: Text
children.value: They stayed here for a time. But then where?

children.name: Text
children.value: They took this path— tough with things to carry, I fear for them.

children.name: Text
children.value: The snow dunes... I fear for them.

children.name: Text
children.value: We warned them about the dunes. They did not listen.

children.name: Text
children.value: They dropped it all to make the difficult climb.

children.name: Text
children.value: I don't know how, but some of them made it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Bear country. Hunters must be strong to come here.

children.name: Text
children.value: The bear deserves respect. Nanuk is like one of us.

children.name: Text
children.value: A storm rises. Your bird will rock like a feather in the wind.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gone is hope, the domain of night belongs to Amarok.

children.name: Text
children.value: The men who followed your Faithful here, can be men no longer.

children.name: Text
children.value: Where did he think he was leading them?

children.name: Text
children.value: There! Long dead, but moving still.

children.name: Text
children.value: Amarok spared them so that their story may be retold.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ooof, that's very good to know…!

children.name: Text
children.value: I can rest easy knowing that's settled!

children.name: Text
children.value: There's something to write home about!

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm not sure that's how it's supposed to be…

children.name: Text
children.value: I wish I'd known when I signed up...

children.name: Text
children.value: How will we get through this…?

children.name: Text
children.value: As if we didn't have enough worries…

children.name: Text
children.value: I always knew you could make it.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'll follow your footsteps in the snow!

children.name: Text
children.value: I will do my best too!

children.name: Text
children.value: I will make you proud as well!

children.name: Text
children.value: How did y-…!? How could y-…?

children.name: Text
children.value: You're leaving us all out in the cold!

children.name: Text
children.value: Thank you, thank you so much.

children.name: Text
children.value: Thank you for thinking of us!

children.name: Text
children.value: We couldn't do this without you!

children.name: Text
children.value: Makes my day a good bit easier.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nah-koor-meek… Did I say that correctly?

children.name: Text
children.value: We look out for each other.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, this? It's only a sketch. My father used to draw the birds he spotted on our trips and I followed suit.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm very glad Old Nate's around, his chuckles are contagious.

children.name: Text
children.value: I never saw stars as sharp as they are here…

children.name: Text
children.value: Yesterday I didn't burst into tears at any point, must mean I'm getting used to this.

children.name: Text
children.value: I've been meaning to ask the technician about his work, but he keeps shooing me away…!

children.name: Text
children.value: Is that technician gone already…? Good...

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm sure technicians know what they're doing, but do they have to say things like that…?

children.name: Text
children.value: Lady Jane is so impressive. I can't imagine what I would do if my little brother went missing…

children.name: Text
children.value: Sometimes I sneak into the hangar just to watch Old Nate ordering the technicians about.

children.name: Text
children.value: I tried rubbing my coat with fish oil to repel water, just like the Inuit do. But now it's all smelly…

children.name: Text
children.value: When I feel I can't keep going, I read a page from The Journey of Victory Ashen — one of the great explorers. I've come to keep that book very close.

children.name: Text
children.value: I saw two tiny arctic foxes in their summer coats the other day. One for the sketchbook.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah, to be tightly-wrapped in my sleeping bag after a long day of work... I could stay forever inside that furry cocoon.

children.name: Text
children.value: My brother will be turning eleven soon! I hope the shark's tooth gets there in time...

children.name: Text
children.value: I had dreamt of sledding, climbing and mountaineering. But we won't get much of that, will we?

children.name: Text
children.value: Maybe one day a little girl will read about me and be inspired to follow in my snowy footsteps…

children.name: Text
children.value: I may have forgotten what it's like to feel my nose.

children.name: Text
children.value: Is it… Is it colder inside than out?!

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm trying to keep moving, but I can't shake the cold.

children.name: Text
children.value: I thought Victory Ashen's descriptions of the arctic cold were literary exaggerations...!

children.name: Text
children.value: I never imagined I could be colder than that February night we camped in the Lakes…

children.name: Text
children.value: Could I beg a second of your time…?

children.name: Text
children.value: I have to admit, I can't do this on my own…

children.name: Text
children.value: It would make life up here much easier…

children.name: Text
children.value: It's not something I can do alone…

children.name: Text
children.value: It would take a terrible weight off my shoulders...

children.name: Text
children.value: If there's anything I can do to help...

children.name: Text
children.value: That you're willing to try means a lot to me.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can do anything you set out to!

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you think you'll have time to spare soon…?

children.name: Text
children.value: I should never have troubled you in the first place...

children.name: Text
children.value: Looks like you have something to report!

children.name: Text
children.value: Did something peek its nose from the seal hole?

children.name: Text
children.value: What did you find in the snow?

children.name: Text
children.value: I feel I can keep pushing on now.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's nice to know I'm not alone out here.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is their last known location…

children.name: Text
children.value: I would like you to have this.

children.name: Text
children.value: I thought you might appreciate it.

children.name: Text
children.value: We're here, the Arctic. This is where our adventure begins!

children.name: Text
children.value: We'll all die here, won't we?

children.name: Text
children.value: I want to go home, please let me go home.

children.name: Text
children.value: No human being can survive this…

children.name: Text
children.value: Will I ever see my family again…?

children.name: Text
children.value: What am I going to tell father…?

children.name: Text
children.value: Whyever did I think of coming here…!?

children.name: Text
children.value: None of my books mentioned just how cold…

children.name: Text
children.value: Uncle was right, I should never have enrolled.

children.name: Text
children.value: I thought I could do this…

children.name: Text
children.value: The cold will kill us all…

children.name: Text
children.value: I won't be able to keep this up much longer…

children.name: Text
children.value: It's so cold. It's just so cold...

children.name: Text
children.value: I can do it, I can do it….

children.name: Text
children.value: Could people get used to this?

children.name: Text
children.value: It's the Arctic; I expected a struggle.

children.name: Text
children.value: Never mind my feelings, there's so much to do.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope we do no harm to the Arctic by warming it.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can't believe I'm really here.

children.name: Text
children.value: Adventuring was never likely to be easy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Coming here was a dream, I can have no complaints.

children.name: Text
children.value: Warmth in the camp at least.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm glad of the heaters, ugly though they be.

children.name: Text
children.value: I warm by the stove after a long day.

children.name: Text
children.value: At least there's a faint heat.

children.name: Text
children.value: I won't surrender while there's shelter.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, no, the furs are burning...!

children.name: Text
children.value: The supplies! Don't let it get to them!

children.name: Text
children.value: Put it out, put it out!

children.name: Text
children.value: I pray we don't pass this to the Inuit...!

children.name: Text
children.value: Is this how my adventure ends…?

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm... so cold... and... so hot...

children.name: Text
children.value: I may not see my family again…

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm already wearing six thick layers...

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm not sure the foreman will be sympathetic…

children.name: Text
children.value: Uncle was right, I'm too weak…

children.name: Text
children.value: We can't just cut across the snow…!

children.name: Text
children.value: Have you tried walking on ice?

children.name: Text
children.value: But we don't have a road.

children.name: Text
children.value: The dogs can't even find the way!

children.name: Text
children.value: You might want to look away for a moment…

children.name: Text
children.value: Watch your step! You wouldn't be the first to slip there…

children.name: Text
children.value: It is not pleasant work...eugh...but someone has to do it.

children.name: Text
children.value: … Is there something wrong with the way I'm doing things?

children.name: Text
children.value: I lost all sensation in my hands long ago! Haha…

children.name: Text
children.value: Sink the knife in the bend of the leg!? Ohhhh…

children.name: Text
children.value: They told me not to pet the sled dogs, but...

children.name: Text
children.value: After the process, it is soft and warm, but...

children.name: Text
children.value: I dearly want to pat the seals on the head and throw them treats.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ahh, I could be hiking to the north pole right now...

children.name: Text
children.value: The oil! Don't let it reach the oil!

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope we don't have to quarantine...

children.name: Text
children.value: This work needs a steadier hand...

children.name: Text
children.value: You asked us to stop, If I remember rightly.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you don't want it, we won't produce it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Something I can do? Not yet...?

children.name: Text
children.value: Good. I'll...wipe this off my hands then.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have so many coats on I can hardly bend...

children.name: Text
children.value: We're trying to stay close, keep each other warm...

children.name: Text
children.value: I haven't seen any on my walks...

children.name: Text
children.value: This isn't the right habitat for them...

children.name: Text
children.value: Are you sure they're from around here...?

children.name: Text
children.value: They don't have enough space in which to roam.

children.name: Text
children.value: I would love to let them run wild...

children.name: Text
children.value: We can't just breed them indoors...!

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope the extremes haven't put them off…

children.name: Text
children.value: We don't have all we need.

children.name: Text
children.value: We are still waiting for materials…

children.name: Text
children.value: We've run low on some of the constituents.

children.name: Text
children.value: We'll have to take it to a warehouse at some stage...

children.name: Text
children.value: We can't store it here forever.

children.name: Text
children.value: I think we have enough of that for a while...

children.name: Text
children.value: We'll have to stop until we have more space.

children.name: Text
children.value: There's been an avalanche in the storeroom!

children.name: Text
children.value: If I'm sending mother and father a photograph, I want them to see me smiling.

children.name: Text
children.value: I will relish every memory of the Arctic I can.

children.name: Text
children.value: My family will be celebrating little brother's birthday. If only I had a tiny window to feel I'm there with them...

children.name: Text
children.value: There is so much the Inuit can teach us.

children.name: Text
children.value: People are ignorant about Inuit life.

children.name: Text
children.value: I do miss it— though honestly, I'd be fine without...

children.name: Text
children.value: I've thought of something — something that'll make things a lot easier for all of us!

children.name: Text
children.value: Father wanted a sketch of this animal, but I haven't spotted one yet. Do let me know, if you see one!

children.name: Text
children.value: My friend Arno and his research group haven't returned and it's getting late...

children.name: Text
children.value: The researchers should be here... Where could they have gone?

children.name: Text
children.value: Signs of a bear attack! Oh, no, Arno...!

children.name: Text
children.value: They must be nearby! They have to be...!

children.name: Text
children.value: Arno is safe! They all are! Thank you, you saved them from Nanuk.

children.name: Text
children.value: Father told me the great auk are gravely endangered. Soon, none will be left...

children.name: Text
children.value: An exploration party is gathering to reach the north pole by sled. I told them you might be able to help...

children.name: Text
children.value: Remember that party of explorers who set out for the North Pole? We've had no news from them in a while...

children.name: Text
children.value: This is good ice, solid ice. Perfect for building an igloo.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, no! Have we come too late?

children.name: Text
children.value: It's a miracle they survived. Maybe they should have asked you to drop them a little further north...

children.name: Text
children.value: Was that...? No, couldn't have been...

children.name: Text
children.value: Many previous expeditions became lost in the ice. Most were forced to leave valuable resources behind— we could look for them?

children.name: Text
children.value: The great Sir William Perry had to abandon his ship too— HMS Angry Wrath. It must still be out here somewhere...

children.name: Text
children.value: I grew up reenacting his expeditions in the garden, I can still recite the coordinates of the Angry Wrath by heart!

children.name: Text
children.value: The HMS Angry Wrath! Such history. Oh yes, of course, the scrap will be useful too! Why not take it to Old Nate?

children.name: Text
children.value: The expedition must have been really stubborn to venture up there.

children.name: Text
children.value: I find such details just fascinating.

children.name: Text
children.value: The sacrifices I made to be here...

children.name: Text
children.value: What we need is fifty words for shit.

children.name: Text
children.value: I blame it on those young twits.

children.name: Text
children.value: It all smacks of desperation really.

children.name: Text
children.value: Doesn't this worry you at all?

children.name: Text
children.value: What's the point of all this?

children.name: Text
children.value: Why are we even here, in fact?

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you drag this on forever?

children.name: Text
children.value: As welcome as a tot of the good stuff.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hydrogen, if handled correctly, poses no risk to airships whatsover.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm a first-class scientist who happens to be eminently practical.

children.name: Text
children.value: These young explorers can really be quite, quite, naïve.

children.name: Text
children.value: You see some people want to go flying into every situation, before they've understood it doesn't work like that.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's fortunate I'm able to bring much-needed experience and composure to an otherwise amateurish operation.

children.name: Text
children.value: Most don't know the first thing about the science behind zeppelineering: that's why I'm here.

children.name: Text
children.value: The evidence against O.D.H.Dickinson's arguments in the field of zeppelineering grow by the day.

children.name: Text
children.value: I do find if I affect a plummy voice, people think I know what I'm talking about.

children.name: Text
children.value: Those young explorers take everything personally, I just think it's pathetic.

children.name: Text
children.value: …and that's the funny thing, so few of the finds out here should surprise if you've done your research…

children.name: Text
children.value: They're whirling dervishes in a tea room, pulling knobs and levers whose functions they scarcely understand.

children.name: Text
children.value: The remarkable rock strata were only accessible from the polynya. I had to improvise a foundation in geology for the stupids.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm no zany inventor, dear me, no—no need for imagination whatsoever, it's exact, often tedious work.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sir John Faithful's expedition was to catalog the Arctic in every detail; I'd have enjoyed that sort of freedom myself...

children.name: Text
children.value: This Spoondrift character has no scientific credentials whatsoever, and yet he has been put in charge.

children.name: Text
children.value: What can I say, I'm a balloonatic.

children.name: Text
children.value: Bring in top mechanics, leave them out in the cold…

children.name: Text
children.value: How can one operate machinery, when one has a case of the dithers?

children.name: Text
children.value: Note please, the horripilation of my dextral epiderm!

children.name: Text
children.value: I could describe in microscopic detail what is happening to my poor body, but I doubt you'd understand.

children.name: Text
children.value: A hard rime has formed upon my brow.

children.name: Text
children.value: Perhaps if I were frozen, some future scientist could reanimate me, so that I may witness  the 25th century.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't deal with it like Spoondrift would.

children.name: Text
children.value: Needs taking apart, and putting back together again.

children.name: Text
children.value: I do have one or two concerns…

children.name: Text
children.value: It is proving a bit of a puzzle…

children.name: Text
children.value: In this, you may have more experience than I, possibly…

children.name: Text
children.value: The salient issue of the moment, I'd say…

children.name: Text
children.value: Passion for the subject is essential.

children.name: Text
children.value: I won't presume 'til I hear further news.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't let this miserable place put you off.

children.name: Text
children.value: Going about it with due rigour, I hope?

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't let it drag on forever.

children.name: Text
children.value: The sun doesn't go down, but time still passes.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's like dealing with the undergraduates.

children.name: Text
children.value: Went down like a lead balloon.

children.name: Text
children.value: Just needed the bare minimum of application.

children.name: Text
children.value: I see you've abandoned the idea.

children.name: Text
children.value: A rigorous examination of the topic.

children.value: The plot, and the snow, thickens.

children.name: Text
children.value: Always willing to share the plaudits.

children.value: Yes I'm a zeppelin technician, but really, I'm much more than that.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'll be going home in a cube.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do I shout 'til I'm blue in the face?!

children.value: Not to be a hyperbore, but it's flipping cold!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Arctic is cold, what a surprise!

children.name: Text
children.value: Just about keeping the wolf from the door…

children.name: Text
children.value: My expectations were low to begin with.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can still feel some of my limbs.

children.name: Text
children.value: My technique against facial frostbite is working.

children.value: The explorers can act as windbreaks if need be.

children.value: This is as forgiving as it gets.

children.value: They didn't use lead in the food tins did they?

children.value: Any form of medical practicioner will do.

children.value: Yes I'm afraid of dying, who wouldn't be?

children.value: Get me on the first boat home.

children.value: I look forward to the high table suppers upon our triumphal return.
